trans-unit.source: Compound forms consist of two components, separated by an equals sign or a colon. The first component is the property name, and the second component is the particular value of the property to match against, for example, \p{Script: Greek} and \p{Script=Greek} both mean to match characters whose Script property value is Greek.
trans-unit.target: 복합 형태 는 등호 또는 콜론으로 구분 된 두 가지 구성 요소로 구성됩니다. 첫 번째 구성 요소는 속성 이름이고, 두 번째 구성 요소는 예를 들어,에 맞게 속성의 특정 값, \p{Script: Greek} 와 \p{Script=Greek} 문자와 일치하는 모두 평균 누구의 스크립트 속성 값 그리스어입니다.

trans-unit.source: Compound forms consist of two components, separated by an equals sign or a colon. The first component is the property name, and the second component is the particular value of the property to match against, for example, \p{Script_Extensions: Greek} and \p{Script_Extensions=Greek} both mean to match characters whose Script_Extensions property value is Greek. (Script_Extensions is an improved version of the Script property.)

trans-unit.source: DB_File allows access to Berkeley DB files using the tie() mechanism in Perl 5 (for full details, see tie()). This facility allows DB_File to access Berkeley DB files using either an associative array (for DB_HASH & DB_BTREE file types) or an ordinary array (for the DB_RECNO file type).
trans-unit.target: DB_File 에서는 Perl 5의 tie () 메커니즘을 사용하여 Berkeley DB 파일에 액세스 할 수 있습니다 (자세한 내용은 tie () 참조 ). 이 기능을 통해 DB_File 은 연관 배열 (DB_HASH & DB_BTREE 파일 유형) 또는 일반 배열 (DB_RECNO 파일 유형)을 사용하여 Berkeley DB 파일에 액세스 할 수 있습니다 .

trans-unit.source: DB_File allows access to Berkeley DB files using the tie() mechanism in Perl 5 (for full details, see "tie()" in perlfunc). This facility allows DB_File to access Berkeley DB files using either an associative array (for DB_HASH & DB_BTREE file types) or an ordinary array (for the DB_RECNO file type).
DB_File comes with the standard Perl source distribution. Look in the directory

trans-unit.source: DB_File is a module which allows Perl programs to make use of the facilities provided by Berkeley DB version 1.x (if you have a newer version of DB, see "Using DB_File with Berkeley DB version 2 or greater"). It is assumed that you have a copy of the Berkeley DB manual pages at hand when reading this documentation. The interface defined here mirrors the Berkeley DB interface closely.

DB_File is a module which allows Perl programs to make use of the facilities provided by Berkeley DB version 1.x (if you have a newer version of DB, see Using DB_File with Berkeley DB version 2 or greater). It is assumed that you have a copy of the Berkeley DB manual pages at hand when reading this documentation. The interface defined here mirrors the Berkeley DB interface closely.
trans-unit.target: DB_File 은 Perl 프로그램이 Berkeley DB 버전 1.x에서 제공하는 기능을 사용할 수 있도록하는 모듈입니다 (최신 버전의 DB가있는 경우 Berkeley DB 버전 2 이상에서 DB_File 사용 참조 ). 이 문서를 읽을 때 Berkeley DB 매뉴얼 페이지 사본이 있다고 가정합니다. 여기에 정의 된 인터페이스는 Berkeley DB 인터페이스를 밀접하게 미러링합니다.

trans-unit.source: DB_File is designed to work with any version of Berkeley DB, but is limited to the functionality provided by version 1. If you want to make use of the new features available in Berkeley DB 2.x, or greater, use the Perl module BerkeleyDB instead.

trans-unit.source: Default: Usually false. If UCA_Version is 22 or 24, and the value of long_contraction is not specified in new() , a true value is set implicitly. This is a workaround to pass Conformance Tests for Unicode 6.0.0 and 6.1.0.

trans-unit.source: Default: Usually false. If UCA_Version is 22 or 24, and the value of long_contraction is not specified in new(), a true value is set implicitly. This is a workaround to pass Conformance Tests for Unicode 6.0.0 and 6.1.0.

Definitions for locales that you use must be installed. You, or your system administrator, must make sure that this is the case. The available locales, the location in which they are kept, and the manner in which they are installed all vary from system to system. Some systems provide only a few, hard-wired locales and do not allow more to be added. Others allow you to add "canned" locales provided by the system supplier. Still others allow you or the system administrator to define and add arbitrary locales. (You may have to ask your supplier to provide canned locales that are not delivered with your operating system.) Read your system documentation for further illumination.
